{id:'q4_go_001',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Digital India',
q:'Digital India Programme\'s three core vision areas are:',
opts:['Make all Indians IT professionals','(1) Digital Infrastructure as a utility for every citizen; (2) Governance and Services on Demand; (3) Digital Empowerment of citizens','Only rural internet connectivity','Only government process digitization'],
ans:1,
explain:'Digital India (2015): Vision: (1) Core Utility Infrastructure (broadband highways, mobile connectivity, public internet, cloud, secure cyberspace); (2) Governance on Demand (integrated e-services); (3) Digital Empowerment (digital literacy, universal access).',
wrongExplain:'Key sub-programmes: BharatNet (rural fiber), Common Service Centres (5 lakh kiosks), DigiLocker, e-Hospital, UMANG, MyGov, National Scholarship Portal. India Stack is the technical foundation.'},

{id:'q4_go_002',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'RTI',
q:'The Central Information Commission (CIC) under RTI Act 2005 is:',
opts:['A constitutional body like CAG','A statutory body — hears second appeals against Public Information Officer and First Appellate Authority decisions; CIC decisions are binding and have civil court powers','Only an advisory body','A part of the Supreme Court'],
ans:1,
explain:'CIC: Statutory body under RTI Act. Chief Information Commissioner + up to 10 Information Commissioners. Has powers of Civil Court. India processes 5-7 crore RTI applications annually.',
wrongExplain:'RTI process: File with PIO → First Appellate Authority → CIC (second appeal). State Information Commissions handle state government RTIs. RTI = one of India\'s most used citizen empowerment laws.'},

{id:'q4_go_003',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'MGNREGA',
q:'MGNREGA 2005 guarantees:',
opts:['365 days/year employment to all rural unemployed','100 days/year of unskilled manual work to any rural household demanding it, at statutory minimum wage — a legal right, not a scheme','50 days/year only to BPL card holders','200 days for SC/ST households in drought areas'],
ans:1,
explain:'MGNREGA: Demand-driven. Any rural household demands work → must receive within 5 km and 15 days, or pay unemployment allowance. ~Rs 70,000-80,000 crore annual expenditure. Largest public employment programme.',
wrongExplain:'MGNREGA: 90% unskilled labor component, 60% wage share. Women must comprise 33% of workers. Work must be within 5 km. If not provided within 15 days: unemployment allowance must be paid.'},

{id:'q4_go_004',subject:'Governance',node:'go3',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Lokpal',
q:'Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act 2013 established Lokpal covering:',
opts:['State governments only','Lokpal at Centre covering PM (with conditions), Ministers, MPs, Group A-D officials, NGOs receiving govt funds — states mandated to have Lokayuktas','Only MPs and Ministers','Only bureaucrats at Secretary level'],
ans:1,
explain:'Lokpal Act 2013 (after Anna Hazare movement): PM covered with restrictions; Union Ministers; MPs; Group A, B, C, D officials; entities funded by government. First Lokpal appointed 2019 (Justice Pinaki Chandra Ghose).',
wrongExplain:'Lokpal can investigate and refer to CBI. Has prosecution wing. Removal: same as SC judge. States mandated to establish Lokayuktas within 1 year of Act. Most states had Lokayuktas before the Act.'},

{id:'q4_go_005',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'CSC',
q:'Common Service Centres (CSCs) in India are:',
opts:['Government offices in each taluka','Village-level entrepreneur-operated (VLE) kiosks providing government and private services digitally to rural citizens — part of Digital India\'s last-mile delivery','Only banking correspondent outlets','Only health service delivery points'],
ans:1,
explain:'CSC 2.0: ~5 lakh kiosks. VLEs (Village Level Entrepreneurs) are self-employed. Services: Aadhaar update, PAN, certificates, PM-KISAN, banking, insurance, telemedicine, education. Reaches ~3 crore citizens daily.',
wrongExplain:'CSCs are the physical touchpoints of Digital India in rural areas. VLE earns commission. Government targets 1 CSC per Gram Panchayat. CSCs also serve as banking correspondents for Jan Dhan accounts.'},

{id:'q4_go_006',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Lateral Entry',
q:'Lateral Entry into the civil services (2018 onwards) was introduced to:',
opts:['Replace IAS officers completely','Bring domain expertise from private sector/academia/NGOs for specialized Joint Secretary/Deputy Secretary positions — addressing skill gaps in technical governance','Train IAS officers in private sector methods','Merge IPS and IAS cadres'],
ans:1,
explain:'Lateral Entry: JS-level positions advertised for 35-45 year professionals from private sector, academia, NGOs. Purpose: domain expertise in AI, economics, environment where generalist IAS may lack depth.',
wrongExplain:'2nd ARC recommended lateral entry. Controversy: bypasses reservation system (lateral entrants don\'t go through UPSC). Accountability concerns. Knowledge continuity issues when lateral entrants leave.'},

{id:'q4_go_007',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'District Planning',
q:'District Planning Committees (DPC) under Art 243ZD must include:',
opts:['Only government officials','At least 4/5 of members elected from Panchayat and Municipal members in the district — consolidates rural and urban development plans','Only civil society representatives','Equal members from Centre and State'],
ans:1,
explain:'DPC: Minimum 80% elected from PRIs + ULBs in the district. Chairperson elected by DPC members. Prepares draft development plan for the whole district. Bridges rural-urban planning divide.',
wrongExplain:'74th Amendment created municipal structures. 73rd created PRIs. DPC = bridge. But DPCs rarely function as envisioned — gap between constitutional provision and ground reality is a governance challenge.'},

{id:'q4_go_008',subject:'Governance',node:'go3',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Enforcement Directorate',
q:'The Enforcement Directorate (ED) primarily operates under:',
opts:['CBI Act','Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA) 2002 + Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA) 1999 — under Ministry of Finance','Income Tax Act','Indian Penal Code for corruption'],
ans:1,
explain:'ED: PMLA 2002 (investigate money laundering, attach properties) + FEMA 1999 (forex violations). Under Ministry of Finance. Can arrest without warrant in PMLA cases. Attach + confiscate proceeds of crime.',
wrongExplain:'CBI = corruption + serious crimes (IPC, CrPC, under MHA technically but PMO-controlled). ED = money laundering + forex. Different laws, different agencies, sometimes overlapping investigations.'},

{id:'q4_go_009',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'NCW',
q:'National Commission for Women (NCW) is:',
opts:['A constitutional body under Art 338','A statutory body under NCW Act 1990 — examines safeguards for women, reviews legislation, recommends policy changes, hears complaints','Only an advisory body with no legal powers','A body within Ministry of Home Affairs'],
ans:1,
explain:'NCW (established 1992): Statutory body under NCW Act 1990. Investigates complaints, reviews laws, recommends safeguards, takes suo motu cognizance of violations. Cannot prosecute directly — refers to police.',
wrongExplain:'NCW vs NCSC vs NHRC: NCW = women\'s rights (statutory). NCSC = SC rights (constitutional). NHRC = human rights generally (statutory). Know the legal basis for each.'},

{id:'q4_go_010',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'CPGRAMS',
q:'CPGRAMS (Centralized Public Grievance Redress and Monitoring System) is:',
opts:['Courts case management portal','Online platform for citizens to file grievances against Central Government departments — 30-day resolution target, progress tracked, ministry-wise accountability','Police complaint registration portal','State government portal only'],
ans:1,
explain:'CPGRAMS: Citizens file complaints → auto-routed to concerned ministry/department → 30-day response mandatory. Over 25 crore grievances filed. Integrated with PMO review (PRAGATI platform).',
wrongExplain:'PRAGATI = PM-chaired review of flagship programmes and infrastructure projects (different from CPGRAMS). CPGRAMS = citizen-facing grievance platform. MyGov = citizen engagement platform. All are distinct.'},

{id:'q4_go_011',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'FRA Rights',
q:'Forest Rights Act 2006 recognizes which categories of rights?',
opts:['Only land ownership rights','Individual Forest Rights (IFR) + Community Forest Rights (CFR) including rights to protect, manage and govern forest resources + habitat rights for PTGs','Only grazing rights','Mining rights in forest areas'],
ans:1,
explain:'FRA 2006: IFR (cultivated land up to 4 ha), CFR (community forest resource management rights), habitat rights for Particularly Vulnerable Tribal Groups (PVTGs), conversion of forest villages to revenue villages.',
wrongExplain:'FRA corrected "historical injustice" of colonial-era forest laws that denied forest communities\' rights. Implementation contested: Gram Sabhas approve claims but Forest Advisory Committee rejections remain high.'},

{id:'q4_go_012',subject:'Governance',node:'go3',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'SEBI',
q:'SEBI (Securities and Exchange Board of India) is:',
opts:['A constitutional body like CAG or ECI','A statutory regulatory body under SEBI Act 1992 — regulates stock markets, mutual funds, investment advisers, corporate governance','A department within RBI','Only an advisory body for stock exchanges'],
ans:1,
explain:'SEBI (1988 executive body, 1992 statutory): Three-in-one powers: quasi-legislative (regulations), quasi-judicial (adjudication), quasi-executive (investigation). HQ Mumbai. Protects investor interests.',
wrongExplain:'Financial sector regulators: RBI (banking), SEBI (securities), IRDAI (insurance), PFRDA (pension), IBC (insolvency). Each has separate statutory backing. FSDC (Financial Stability and Development Council) coordinates.'},

{id:'q4_go_013',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Aspirational Districts',
q:'The Aspirational Districts Programme (ADP) of NITI Aayog focuses on:',
opts:['Only economically rich districts for investment','115 most underdeveloped districts — ranked monthly on 49 indicators across health+nutrition, education, agriculture, financial inclusion, infrastructure, skills','Capital cities of states only','Coastal districts for port development'],
ans:1,
explain:'ADP (2018): Bottom 10% districts. Monthly ranking creates "race to the top" competition. Champion Secretaries at Centre + government mentors at state level. Convergence of Central schemes approach.',
wrongExplain:'ADP districts: Aspirational Districts → Aspiring India. Programme uses SDG-aligned indicators. Success: rapid improvement in child stunting, institutional delivery, financial inclusion in many districts.'},

{id:'q4_go_014',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'DigiLocker',
q:'Documents on DigiLocker from registered issuers are:',
opts:['For viewing only, not legally valid','Legally equivalent to original documents under IT Act amendment — accepted at airports, banks, courts for KYC and identity verification','Only valid for government services','Only for educational certificates'],
ans:1,
explain:'DigiLocker: Documents from registered issuers (CBSE, MCA, transport authorities, income tax) are legally original under IT Act. Accepted: airports for boarding, banks for KYC, courts, police verification.',
wrongExplain:'Ministry of Education mandated DigiLocker for CBSE marksheets. Driving Licence and Vehicle RC on DigiLocker valid for traffic police checks. Removes need for physical documents.'},

{id:'q4_go_015',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'ONORC',
q:'One Nation One Ration Card (ONORC) scheme enables:',
opts:['New ration cards for everyone in India','Portability of PDS entitlements — migrant workers can access subsidized food grains from any Fair Price Shop anywhere in India using Aadhaar-based authentication','Only BPL family benefits to be portable','Doubling of ration entitlement'],
ans:1,
explain:'ONORC: Migrant workers can access their home state PDS entitlement from any FPS in India. Aadhaar POS authentication. All states/UTs implemented. ~2 crore beneficiaries using portability monthly.',
wrongExplain:'ONORC solved a key problem: migrant construction/domestic workers could not access their home state ration from their work location. Combination of Aadhaar + digital FPS = national portability.'},

{id:'q4_go_016',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'CAG',
q:'The Comptroller and Auditor General of India (CAG) audits:',
opts:['Only Central Government departments','All expenditure from Consolidated Fund of India + all State Consolidated Funds + bodies substantially funded by government — most comprehensive audit authority','Only Public Sector Undertakings','Only Union Finance Accounts'],
ans:1,
explain:'CAG (Art 148): External auditor of entire government — Central + all 28 State CFs + UT CFs + substantially funded bodies. CAG reports tabled in Parliament → PAC (Public Accounts Committee) examines.',
wrongExplain:'CAG = independent (removed only like SC judge). CAG reports: Union Finance Accounts, Compliance Audit, Performance Audit, Audit of PSUs. Parliament receives CAG report → PAC scrutinizes → government must respond.'},

{id:'q4_go_017',subject:'Governance',node:'go3',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Fast Track Courts',
q:'Fast Track Special Courts (FTSCs) in India were primarily established for:',
opts:['Civil property disputes for quick settlement','Sexual assault cases (POCSO) and rape cases after Nirbhaya case 2012 — also: cases against sitting MPs/MLAs, SC/ST atrocities cases','Traffic violation cases','Tax dispute resolution'],
ans:1,
explain:'FTSCs: Post-Nirbhaya (2012) for POCSO + rape cases. Supreme Court directed fast-tracking cases against legislators. FTCs for SC/ST atrocities. Aim: reduce pendency in serious offence categories.',
wrongExplain:'India total pending cases: ~5 crore. Lok Adalats = pre-litigation settlement. NCLT/NCLAT = commercial disputes. Gram Nyayalaya = village-level. FTCs = specific serious offence categories.'},

{id:'q4_go_018',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'PRAGATI',
q:'PRAGATI (Pro-Active Governance And Timely Implementation) platform is:',
opts:['A state-level grievance portal','PM-chaired monthly video-conference platform for tracking central + state government infrastructure projects and flagged programmes using real-time GIS data','A judicial case tracking system','A social media platform for government'],
ans:1,
explain:'PRAGATI: PM chairs monthly with state CMs and central secretaries. Reviews stalled infrastructure projects (worth Rs 14+ lakh crore reviewed since 2015). Uses GIS, satellite data, video-conferencing.',
wrongExplain:'PRAGATI ≠ CPGRAMS (citizen grievances). PRAGATI = project monitoring. Enables PM-level direct intervention to unblock projects. Success: several long-pending railway, road, power projects unblocked.'},

{id:'q4_go_019',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'NHRC',
q:'National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) was established under:',
opts:['Article 338 of the Constitution','Protection of Human Rights Act 1993 — can investigate violations by government agencies, police; cannot directly investigate armed forces','Executive order of President','Supreme Court direction in a specific case'],
ans:1,
explain:'NHRC: Statutory under PHRA 1993. Chaired by retired CJI + retired SC/HC judges. Can investigate, call for reports, recommend compensation. Annual report to Parliament.',
wrongExplain:'NHRC jurisdiction: Complaints of human rights violations by state/central government agencies. Most common: police atrocities, custodial deaths, bonded labour. Cannot directly investigate Armed Forces — can seek reports from Ministry of Defence.'},

{id:'q4_go_020',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'RPWD Act',
q:'Rights of Persons with Disabilities Act 2016 expanded recognized disabilities from 7 to:',
opts:['10','14','21','30'],
ans:2,
explain:'RPWD 2016 replaced PDA 1995. Added: acid attack victims, Parkinson\'s, sickle cell disease, intellectual disability, dwarfism, muscular dystrophy, multiple sclerosis, thalassemia. Aligns with UN CRPD.',
wrongExplain:'RPWD 2016 also: increased reservation from 3% to 4% in government jobs; mandatory accessibility for built environment; penal provisions for discrimination. India ratified CRPD (UN Convention on Rights of Persons with Disabilities) in 2007.'},

{id:'q4_go_021',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2022,topic:'BharatNet',
q:'BharatNet project aims to:',
opts:['Provide 4G mobile coverage everywhere','Connect all 2.5 lakh+ Gram Panchayats with high-speed optical fiber broadband — backbone for rural digital services delivery','Build 5G towers in cities only','Connect all district headquarters'],
ans:1,
explain:'BharatNet (2011): Largest rural broadband connectivity project globally. Optical fiber to all Gram Panchayats. Enables: telemedicine, e-education, government services, e-commerce in villages.',
wrongExplain:'BharatNet provides the fiber backbone. CSCs provide the last-mile physical service delivery. PM-WANI (WiFi Access Network Interface) enables local WiFi hotspots on BharatNet fiber. Together = rural digital infrastructure.'},

{id:'q4_go_022',subject:'Governance',node:'go3',difficulty:'hard',year:2021,topic:'Regulatory Bodies',
q:'Which regulatory body is correctly matched with its statutory authority?',
opts:['TRAI — Banking Regulation Act 1949','IRDAI — Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority Act 1999','SEBI — RBI Act 1934','CCI — Securities Contracts Regulation Act'],
ans:1,
explain:'IRDAI: IRDAI Act 1999. Regulates insurance companies, brokers, agents. HQ Hyderabad. SEBI = SEBI Act 1992. TRAI = TRAI Act 1997. CCI = Competition Act 2002.',
wrongExplain:'Sector regulators: RBI (banking/NBFCs under RBI Act 1934), SEBI (securities/mutual funds), IRDAI (insurance), PFRDA (pensions under PFRDA Act 2013), IBBI (insolvency under IBC 2016).'},

{id:'q4_go_023',subject:'Governance',node:'go4',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Mission Karmayogi',
q:'Mission Karmayogi (National Programme for Civil Services Capacity Building) focuses on:',
opts:['Physical fitness training for all government employees','Competency-based training for 46 lakh central government employees through iGOT-Karmayogi online platform — shifting from rules-based to roles-based approach','Recruitment reform for IAS','Salary revision for government employees'],
ans:1,
explain:'Mission Karmayogi (2020): iGOT (Integrated Government Online Training) Karmayogi platform. PM-chaired PM Human Resources Council. 4 institutions to anchor capacity building. Domain-specific competency framework.',
wrongExplain:'Karmayogi Bharat = the SPV implementing iGOT platform. Mission targets: civil servant with right attitude, skills, knowledge for 21st century governance. Includes: lateral entrants + career civil servants.'},

{id:'q4_go_024',subject:'Governance',node:'go2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Social Protection',
q:'e-Shram Portal (2021) was created to:',
opts:['Register only MGNREGA workers','Create a national database of unorganized workers (building, agriculture, domestic, street vendors) linked to Aadhaar — enable targeted social protection delivery','Replace all social welfare schemes','Register only industrial workers'],
ans:1,
explain:'e-Shram Portal: Unorganized sector workers = ~38 crore. Registration links to Aadhaar. Enables: PMSBY (accident insurance), PMASBY (pension), targeted scheme delivery. Pandemic revealed lack of data on migrant/unorganized workers.',
wrongExplain:'COVID-19 exposed: India had no data on migrant workers or unorganized sector. e-Shram fills this gap. NDUW (National Database of Unorganised Workers). Portal has 29+ crore registered workers.'},

{id:'q4_go_025',subject:'Governance',node:'go1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Transparency',
q:'Government e-Marketplace (GeM) portal was created to:',
opts:['Allow citizens to buy government assets','Enable government ministries and departments to procure goods and services online — transparent, competitive, eliminating middlemen in government procurement','Only for defence procurement','Only for Central Government, not states'],
ans:1,
explain:'GeM (2016): Online marketplace for government procurement. Vendors register, list products at competitive prices. Government buyers compare and purchase. Rs 2.5 lakh crore+ annual GMV. Reduces procurement time and corruption.',
wrongExplain:'GeM replaced: DGS&D (Directorate General of Supplies and Disposals). Mandatory for goods/services available on GeM. Includes: MSMEs, startups, self-help groups as sellers. States also now use GeM.'},

