{id:'q4_ir_001',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Neighbourhood First',
q:'India\'s "Neighbourhood First" policy was announced by:',
opts:['Manmohan Singh government in 2004','PM Modi — inaugurated in 2014 by inviting all SAARC leaders to swearing-in ceremony; prioritizes South Asian neighbours in foreign engagement','Indira Gandhi in the 1970s','Rajiv Gandhi in 1985'],
ans:1,
explain:'Neighbourhood First (2014): All SAARC leaders invited to PM Modi\'s swearing-in. Prioritizes Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar, Maldives. Builds on Gujral Doctrine (1996) of non-reciprocity with smaller neighbours.',
wrongExplain:'Gujral Doctrine: India should give without expecting reciprocity from smaller neighbours. Neighbourhood First = proactive engagement with all neighbours. Countering China\'s growing influence is also a driver.'},

{id:'q4_ir_002',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'G20 Presidency',
q:'India\'s G20 Presidency (2023) was themed around:',
opts:['Trade Liberalization and Economic Growth','Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam (One Earth, One Family, One Future) — championed Global South, DPI, climate finance, food security','Military alliances and security','Nuclear disarmament'],
ans:1,
explain:'India\'s G20 2023: African Union admitted as permanent member (India\'s diplomatic win). Global Biofuels Alliance launched. DPI (India Stack model) adopted as G20 framework. Delhi Declaration on Russia-Ukraine = diplomatic balancing.',
wrongExplain:'G20 = 19 countries + EU (now + African Union). Represents 85% world GDP. India hosted "Voice of Global South Summit" separately. India bridged Global South demands with G7 positions.'},

{id:'q4_ir_003',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'AUKUS',
q:'AUKUS (2021) primarily involves:',
opts:['A trade agreement between three countries','Nuclear-powered submarine technology transfer from USA and UK to Australia + advanced defence cooperation (AI, quantum, cyber, hypersonic missiles)','A climate finance agreement','Extension of the Five Eyes intelligence sharing'],
ans:1,
explain:'AUKUS (September 2021): USA + UK help Australia acquire nuclear-powered (not nuclear-armed) submarines. Also: AI, quantum, cyber, hypersonic. Angered France (lost $90B conventional submarine contract).',
wrongExplain:'AUKUS ≠ Five Eyes (5-country intelligence). AUKUS ≠ Quad (4-country strategic dialogue). AUKUS = specific advanced defence tech partnership. India not part of AUKUS but welcomed it as Indo-Pacific balance.'},

{id:'q4_ir_004',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir1',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Kalapani',
q:'The Kalapani territorial dispute between India and Nepal involves:',
opts:['Maritime boundary in Bay of Bengal','Tri-junction area (India-Nepal-China) where Nepal claims territory per 1816 Sugauli Treaty; escalated when India published new map in 2019 including Kalapani in Indian territory','River water sharing agreement dispute','Air space rights above Himalayas'],
ans:1,
explain:'Kalapani (~35 sq km): Nepal claims per Sugauli Treaty (1816) which defined boundary along Kali/Mahakali river. India published new map (2019) showing Kalapani in India → Nepal published own competing map.',
wrongExplain:'Lipulekh pass (within Kalapani area) = on India\'s Kailash-Mansarovar route. Nepal objected to India-China 2020 agreement on Lipulekh. Strategic: India uses area for border patrol. Resolution requires bilateral talks.'},

{id:'q4_ir_005',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'UNSC Reform',
q:'India\'s campaign for permanent UN Security Council membership is based on:',
opts:['Nuclear weapon possession','World\'s largest democracy + 3rd largest PPP economy + largest UN peacekeeping contributor + 1.4 billion population + founding UN member + leadership of Global South','Hosting UN agencies in India','Military strength ranking'],
ans:1,
explain:'India\'s UNSC case: Population (18% world), economy (5th nominal/3rd PPP), democracy, largest peacekeeper contributor (historically), founding UN member, leading developing nation voice, G4 group (India, Germany, Japan, Brazil).',
wrongExplain:'P5 (USA, UK, France, Russia, China) have veto powers. China blocks India\'s bid. USA and France support India in principle. NSG membership (nuclear) is a separate diplomatic challenge.'},

{id:'q4_ir_006',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'LAC',
q:'The Line of Actual Control (LAC) is different from an internationally recognized border because:',
opts:['It is an officially demarcated boundary on maps','It has no mutually agreed alignment — India and China have different perceptions in three sectors (Eastern, Middle, Western), leading to periodic friction points','It is a colonial-era boundary accepted by both sides','It is only a ceasefire line like LoC in J&K'],
ans:1,
explain:'LAC: Emerged from 1962 war ceasefire. No joint survey or mutually agreed map. Three sectors: Eastern (Arunachal, Sikkim), Middle (HP, Uttarakhand), Western (Ladakh = most contested). Galwan 2020 = worst clash since 1975.',
wrongExplain:'McMahon Line (1914) = India-China boundary in Eastern sector per Simla Convention. China doesn\'t recognize it. Western sector: India claims up to Aksai Chin (China-controlled). Patrol points define competing claims.'},

{id:'q4_ir_007',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir4',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'R2P',
q:'The "Responsibility to Protect" (R2P) doctrine means:',
opts:['A country\'s duty to protect its military assets abroad','International community\'s responsibility to intervene when a state fails to protect its citizens from genocide, war crimes, ethnic cleansing, crimes against humanity','WTO trade protection rules for domestic industry','Nuclear states\' obligation to protect non-nuclear allies'],
ans:1,
explain:'R2P (2005 UN World Summit): Three pillars — (1) State protects its citizens; (2) International community assists; (3) International community acts if state fails. Used to justify NATO intervention in Libya (2011).',
wrongExplain:'India is cautious about R2P — fears misuse as regime change tool. IBSA group expressed reservations. Sovereignty vs humanitarian intervention remains contested. India favors "responsibility while protecting" framework.'},

{id:'q4_ir_008',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'China Plus One',
q:'India\'s strategy to attract companies relocating from China ("China+1") is supported by:',
opts:['Banning all Chinese goods from India','PLI scheme providing incremental sales incentives + FDI policy liberalization + skill development + infrastructure investment — attracts Apple (Foxconn), Samsung, others','Complete economic decoupling from China','Joining anti-China military alliance'],
ans:1,
explain:'China+1: Companies diversifying supply chains from China to India. Apple (Foxconn in TN/Karnataka), Samsung, global pharma companies moving some production. PLI scheme is key financial incentive.',
wrongExplain:'India-China bilateral trade = ~$130B (2023). Cannot fully decouple. Strategy = reduce dependence in strategic sectors (electronics, pharma APIs, solar panels, telecom) while maintaining trade.'},

{id:'q4_ir_009',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'India-Bangladesh',
q:'India-Bangladesh relationship is called a "model bilateral" because:',
opts:['No disputes at all','Land Boundary Agreement 2015 (resolved 68-year enclave issue) + Ganga Water Treaty + transit connectivity + mutual counterterrorism — despite some pending issues like Teesta','Only growing trade ties','Religious and cultural similarity'],
ans:1,
explain:'India-Bangladesh LBA 2015: Exchanged 111 Indian enclaves in Bangladesh + 51 Bangladesh enclaves in India — resolved colonial-era oddity. Ganga Water Treaty (1996) = Farakka sharing. Transit for India\'s NE through Bangladesh.',
wrongExplain:'Teesta water sharing treaty pending (West Bengal CM objection). Bangladesh-India = largest bilateral connectivity in South Asia. Political transition in Bangladesh (2024) added uncertainty.'},

{id:'q4_ir_010',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'India-Russia Oil',
q:'India\'s continued purchase of discounted Russian crude oil despite Western pressure reflects:',
opts:['India\'s ideological alignment with Russia','Strategic autonomy + energy security pragmatism — Russia offered 20-30% discounted crude; India\'s Rupee-Ruble mechanism bypasses SWIFT sanctions','Pro-Russia anti-Western stance','India\'s opposition to NATO'],
ans:1,
explain:'Post-Ukraine war (2022): Russia offered India discounted crude → India\'s imports from Russia grew from ~2% to ~35-40% of crude basket. Rupee-Ruble settlement developed to avoid SWIFT-based USD transactions.',
wrongExplain:'India abstained on UNGA resolutions on Ukraine. S-400 = CAATSA waiver sought. India\'s multi-alignment: maintains Russia ties (military, energy) while deepening Quad/Western tech partnerships. Balancing act.'},

{id:'q4_ir_011',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir4',difficulty:'medium',year:2020,topic:'Peacekeeping',
q:'India\'s contribution to UN peacekeeping operations has been:',
opts:['Primarily in Europe','Historically among the largest contributors to UNPKO globally — over 200,000 troop contributions since 1956, primarily in Africa and Middle East; 172+ soldiers killed in service','Only in South Asian countries','Only advisory roles, no troops'],
ans:1,
explain:'India: Largest/one of largest UN peacekeeper contributors historically. Served in Congo, Lebanon, South Sudan, Sudan, Somalia, Liberia, Haiti, Kosovo. Soft power tool + practical training for military.',
wrongExplain:'Peacekeeping vs peace enforcement: PKO = consent-based, neutral. India supports sovereignty-respecting peacekeeping. India\'s UN Peacekeeping Training Centre in Pune is globally recognized.'},

{id:'q4_ir_012',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Wassenaar',
q:'The Wassenaar Arrangement, which India joined in 2017, controls:',
opts:['Climate technology sharing','Exports of conventional arms and dual-use goods/technologies (civilian + potential military use) among member states','Nuclear technology trade','A free trade agreement'],
ans:1,
explain:'Wassenaar Arrangement (1996): 42 member nations. Controls exports of conventional weapons + dual-use technologies (software, electronics, sensors, lasers). India joining enabled high-tech imports.',
wrongExplain:'India\'s 4 export control regimes membership: Wassenaar (2017), MTCR (2016), Australia Group (2018). Still seeking NSG (Nuclear Suppliers Group) membership. These memberships signal India as responsible high-tech state.'},

{id:'q4_ir_013',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir1',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'Sri Lanka',
q:'India\'s historical involvement in Sri Lanka\'s ethnic conflict included:',
opts:['Military conquest and annexation of Sri Lanka','Indian Peace Keeping Force (IPKF 1987-1990) + support for 13th Amendment (provincial councils) + Tamil Nadu political sensitivity shaping India\'s policy','Complete non-involvement (strict neutrality)','Only economic support, no political involvement'],
ans:1,
explain:'India-Sri Lanka Tamil issue: IPKF (1987-90) deployed under India-Sri Lanka Accord (Rajiv Gandhi-Jayewardene). 13th Amendment: provincial councils. Rajiv Gandhi assassinated by LTTE (1991). India now designates LTTE as terrorist.',
wrongExplain:'Current issues: Fishermen disputes in Palk Strait (both navies involved), Hambantota port (Chinese factor), debt crisis cooperation (2022), Buddhist heritage (Rameswaram-Colombo ferry). Complex multi-layered relationship.'},

{id:'q4_ir_014',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'India-Pakistan J&K',
q:'India\'s official position on Jammu & Kashmir is:',
opts:['The matter requires UN mediation','J&K legally merged into India through Instrument of Accession (October 1947); Art 370 revocation (2019) is India\'s internal matter; rejects all third-party mediation','India accepts the 1948 UN plebiscite resolution as still valid','J&K is a disputed territory under India\'s temporary administration'],
ans:1,
explain:'India\'s position: Maharaja Hari Singh signed IoA on October 26, 1947 = complete legal merger. Art 370 revocation = constitutional internal matter. Pakistan-occupied Kashmir (PoK) = India\'s territory illegally occupied by Pakistan.',
wrongExplain:'UN Resolution 47 (1948) called for plebiscite. India argues Pakistani troops must withdraw first (never happened). India regularly calls for PoK\'s return. CPEC passes through disputed territory = India\'s objection to BRI.'},

{id:'q4_ir_015',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir4',difficulty:'medium',year:2019,topic:'WTO DSM',
q:'WTO\'s Dispute Settlement Mechanism (DSM) is significant because:',
opts:['Countries can impose tariffs freely after disputes','Provides binding dispute resolution — aggrieved member can challenge trade-distorting measures; Panel → Appellate Body → authorization to retaliate. Currently in crisis due to USA blocking Appellate Body appointments','Only advisory opinions, not binding','Only developed nations can use it'],
ans:1,
explain:'WTO DSM: Unique binding mechanism. USA has blocked AB judges since 2017 → AB non-functional since 2019. MPIA (Multi-Party Interim Appeal Arbitration) = workaround. WTO reform is urgent global priority.',
wrongExplain:'India has used DSM against USA (steel/aluminium tariffs), EU. India has been complained against (sugar subsidies, IT tariffs). DSM crisis = major challenge for rules-based multilateral trading system.'},

{id:'q4_ir_016',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'hard',year:2023,topic:'Africa',
q:'India\'s engagement with Africa is characterized by:',
opts:['Resource extraction and large infrastructure loans','Development partnerships: India-Africa Forum Summits, lines of credit ($29B+), ITEC capacity building, pharmaceutical exports (generic medicines), no conditionalities','Military intervention','Competing with China for resources'],
ans:1,
explain:'India-Africa: IAFS (3 summits held). India offers: concessional credit, ITEC (Indian Technical and Economic Cooperation — 10,000+ training slots/year), generic medicines, IT/digital, solar energy.',
wrongExplain:'India vs China in Africa: China = large infrastructure loans, physical projects. India = capacity building, pharma, IT, South-South cooperation framework. Different development cooperation models.'},

{id:'q4_ir_017',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'BIMSTEC',
q:'India prefers BIMSTEC over SAARC for regional connectivity because:',
opts:['BIMSTEC has more member nations','BIMSTEC (Bangladesh, India, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, Thailand, Nepal, Bhutan) excludes Pakistan — allowing connectivity progress; links South and Southeast Asia','BIMSTEC has more financial resources','BIMSTEC includes China as observer'],
ans:1,
explain:'BIMSTEC: 7 members connecting South and Southeast Asia. Excludes Pakistan = SAARC\'s blocking factor. Enables India\'s Act East Policy. Myanmar + Thailand = gateway to ASEAN. FTA negotiations ongoing.',
wrongExplain:'SAARC = stalled (last summit 2014 in Kathmandu). India-Pakistan tensions paralyze SAARC. India uses BIMSTEC as functional alternative for regional integration excluding Pakistan.'},

{id:'q4_ir_018',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir4',difficulty:'hard',year:2022,topic:'Nuclear NFU',
q:'India\'s "No First Use" (NFU) nuclear policy means:',
opts:['India will never develop nuclear weapons','India will not initiate a nuclear strike — will only respond if attacked with nuclear/biological/chemical weapons with massive retaliation and assured destruction','India will disarm unilaterally','India only uses nuclear energy for electricity'],
ans:1,
explain:'NFU (1999 nuclear doctrine): India will not use nuclear weapons first. But if attacked with nuclear/biological/chemical weapons: "massive retaliation designed to inflict unacceptable damage" is assured.',
wrongExplain:'Pakistan = no NFU (first use possible in conventional war). China = NFU (like India). USA, Russia, France = no NFU commitment. Periodic Indian domestic debates about reviewing NFU — no official change made.'},

{id:'q4_ir_019',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir1',difficulty:'medium',year:2023,topic:'Act East Policy',
q:'India\'s "Act East Policy" replaced "Look East Policy" in 2014. The shift means:',
opts:['India abandoned engagement with Southeast Asia','Upgrade from intent to implementation — deeper trade, investment, connectivity, and strategic partnerships with ASEAN, Japan, South Korea, Australia, Pacific islands','India now opposes ASEAN multilateralism','Military focus replacing economic ties'],
ans:1,
explain:'Look East (Narasimha Rao, 1991): Established engagement with ASEAN. Act East (Modi, 2014): Intensify implementation. India-Myanmar-Thailand highway, Kaladan Multimodal Transit, India-Japan maritime cooperation.',
wrongExplain:'NE India = geographical gateway for Act East. Connectivity via Bangladesh, Myanmar to ASEAN. India catching up to China\'s BRI in SE Asian connectivity. ASEAN-India FTA being upgraded.'},

{id:'q4_ir_020',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir2',difficulty:'hard',year:2020,topic:'Paris Club',
q:'The Paris Club is associated with:',
opts:['Climate negotiations for developing nations','Group of 22 major creditor nations coordinating debt restructuring for countries in financial distress — India is an observer; relevant to Sri Lanka 2022-23 debt crisis','Military alliance of Western nations','Trade preferences for Africa'],
ans:1,
explain:'Paris Club (1956): Informal group of official creditors. Negotiates debt relief with debtor countries. Sri Lanka debt crisis 2022-23: India played key bilateral role (rescheduled $1B+ debt) alongside Paris Club process.',
wrongExplain:'India used Sri Lanka debt crisis diplomatically to deepen ties and counter Chinese debt-trap narrative. China\'s debt restructuring was held separately. India became key player in Sri Lanka\'s IMF bailout enabling process.'},

{id:'q4_ir_021',subject:'Int. Relations',node:'ir3',difficulty:'medium',year:2021,topic:'QUAD',
q:'The Quad (Quadrilateral Security Dialogue) was elevated to leader-level in:',
opts:['2007 when originally formed','2021 — first in-person Summit hosted by President Biden; focus: COVID vaccines, climate, critical technologies, Indo-Pacific infrastructure','2017 when it was revived','2019 at G20 Osaka'],
ans:1,
explain:'Quad: Originally formed 2007 (PM Howard of Australia + PM Abe + PM Singh + President Bush). Died down then revived 2017. First Leader Summit (virtual) March 2021. First in-person September 2021 (Biden, Modi, Morrison, Suga).',
